1
00:00:00,605 --> 00:00:17,449
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sama Sambudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sama Sambudassa

2
00:00:18,272 --> 00:00:26,463
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhassa.

3
00:00:26,964 --> 00:00:31,050
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

4
00:00:34,134 --> 00:00:44,667
So, this evening, for some of you, just a recap, maybe an introduction to these three characteristics of existence.

5
00:00:45,542 --> 00:00:48,887
That's what they're called, three characteristics of existence.

6
00:00:48,906 --> 00:01:01,063
And the place to start really is with the Four Noble Truths, because that's where he delineates, that's where he sort of starts to express his understanding.

7
00:01:01,664 --> 00:01:08,293
And the operative word is dukkha, so we have to really get a hold of that word, dukkha.

8
00:01:08,965 --> 00:01:10,706
It just means hard to bear.

9
00:01:11,248 --> 00:01:13,590
If you were to translate it directly, it's hard to bear.

10
00:01:14,531 --> 00:01:16,153
It used to be translated as suffering.

11
00:01:16,655 --> 00:01:25,706
So when people were told that the Buddha's teaching was there is suffering and this is the cause of suffering, everybody thought it was very pessimistic.

12
00:01:26,427 --> 00:01:35,299
In fact, the first book I read on Buddhism that I remember was one by Dr. Schweitzer, who was a humanist.

13
00:01:35,659 --> 00:01:37,081
Well, he's a Christian, but...

14
00:01:37,349 --> 00:02:03,710
very late in life he trained as a doctor and went to work in Africa and he was known for his humanitarian work and he wrote this book which contrasted Christianity to Buddhism and he declared without a shadow of a doubt that Christianity was life affirmative and Buddhism was life negative life negative so I don't know how I overcame that prejudice but somehow I did

15
00:02:05,513 --> 00:02:08,417
And a lot of it goes back to these early translations.

16
00:02:08,758 --> 00:02:14,466
These days, the most common is unsatisfactoriness.

17
00:02:17,770 --> 00:02:24,400
And then in that first noble truth, he tells us why it's unsatisfactory.

18
00:02:24,639 --> 00:02:26,862
And he talks about dukkha dukkha.

19
00:02:27,704 --> 00:02:31,693
and viparinamadukkha and sankhata or sankharadukkha.

20
00:02:32,433 --> 00:02:38,247
So it's the unsatisfactoriness of pain, suffering etc.

21
00:02:38,808 --> 00:02:39,229
etc.

22
00:02:39,991 --> 00:02:47,146
It's the unsatisfactoriness that is caused through impermanence and it's the unsatisfactoriness caused by

23
00:02:47,650 --> 00:02:51,335
things being compounded, having no substance.

24
00:02:53,138 --> 00:03:13,927
And when he then goes into the second noble truth, that the cause of this is this tanha, this attachment, you see, is not just our attachment to pleasure, it's our attachment to these wrong views, that in fact things do have a certain permanency, that things are truly real,

25
00:03:13,907 --> 00:03:17,411
and have some substance.

26
00:03:18,211 --> 00:03:31,825
See, I was with a friend of mine and we were talking about something and I happened to say, but the body's unreal.

27
00:03:32,866 --> 00:03:35,729
And his father who was standing next to him blurted out, yes it is!

28
00:03:37,311 --> 00:03:37,991
And that was it.

29
00:03:38,372 --> 00:03:39,693
He died within a few weeks of that.

30
00:03:40,433 --> 00:03:41,534
So...

31
00:03:43,455 --> 00:03:48,741
But it was such a punch in the air that the conversation came to an end.

32
00:03:49,262 --> 00:03:51,424
You couldn't go anywhere with that sort of statement.

33
00:03:53,265 --> 00:03:58,770
So, of course, it depends what he meant by real, but definitely it has no ultimate reality.

34
00:03:59,390 --> 00:04:07,258
So, these three characteristics are telling us where our delusions lie.

35
00:04:07,498 --> 00:04:11,302
Delusion, remember, the definition of delusion is you don't know where you're deluded.

36
00:04:12,042 --> 00:04:15,006
If you knew you were deluded, if you knew where you were deluded, you wouldn't be deluded.

37
00:04:15,045 --> 00:04:25,961
You might still suffer from the consequence of delusion, but you wouldn't actually realize that you were deluded, because that's the whole definition of being deluded.

38
00:04:27,303 --> 00:04:36,817
And these three definitions, of course, are defining, trying to define delusion.

39
00:04:37,456 --> 00:04:46,928
or trying to counter-define what in those days they were arguing about was what is substantial, what is ultimate reality.

40
00:04:47,790 --> 00:04:54,139
And the Brahmins opted, or generally speaking, the word was the self, the atta.

41
00:04:55,081 --> 00:04:59,427
This atta, this self, became more and more refined as time came on.

42
00:05:00,208 --> 00:05:07,377
And eventually, both the Brahmins, Brahmanism, which we now call Hinduism,

43
00:05:07,661 --> 00:05:14,353
came to the same understanding as Buddhism, but that's another story as to how it was filched.

44
00:05:15,274 --> 00:05:16,596
We won't go into that.

45
00:05:18,319 --> 00:05:34,345
Anyway, what the Buddha is saying is, if there is something substantial, if there is this self, and we would say in our language a spirit or a soul or something which is eternal, if there is that,

46
00:05:35,658 --> 00:05:38,201
How can we discover it?

47
00:05:38,862 --> 00:05:41,386
Or how can we find out what it is?

48
00:05:43,329 --> 00:05:47,795
And it's the process of negation, which is again the same as in Brahmanism.

49
00:05:48,175 --> 00:05:49,959
So it's not this, not that, you see.

50
00:05:50,579 --> 00:06:04,180
So that process of looking at things and saying not this, not that, is part of the process of wakening up to the way things really are, what we might call reality.

51
00:06:04,716 --> 00:06:20,480
So these three avenues of investigation are really trying to clarify for us what it is that can't be ultimate truth, that can't be, shall we say, a real soul or spirit or self.

52
00:06:21,202 --> 00:06:31,440
And the first one, he starts off with, in the Four Noble Truths, he starts off with the dukkha-dukkhata.

53
00:06:31,461 --> 00:06:35,067
So it's the suffering of ordinary pain and the sorrows of life.

54
00:06:36,250 --> 00:06:44,865
And then the next one is this, the suffering caused by change, and the last one, the cause by insubstantiality.

55
00:06:45,233 --> 00:06:51,903
But when it comes to the practice, it's always anicca which comes first, anicca, dukkha, anatta.

56
00:06:51,923 --> 00:06:59,276
And we chant that in the morning, sabbe sankara anicchati, sabbe sankara dukkhati, sabbe sankara anicchati.

57
00:06:59,755 --> 00:07:10,093
So all compounded things are impermanent, all compounded things are unsatisfactory, all compounded things don't constitute anything substantial or a self.

58
00:07:10,899 --> 00:07:17,487
So why is it that in our practice we actually start with the anicca, with the impermanence?

59
00:07:17,648 --> 00:07:32,526
So if you were to say to anybody in the street, everything changes, nothing is permanent in the universe, and this is the deep teaching of the Buddha, they'd look at you and say, yeah.

60
00:07:33,867 --> 00:07:39,134
I mean, it's not as though people are not aware of change.

61
00:07:40,093 --> 00:07:41,596
But it doesn't change their behaviour.

62
00:07:42,177 --> 00:07:48,788
It doesn't motivate them to look more deeply into their lives.

63
00:07:49,348 --> 00:07:50,230
They just accept it.

64
00:07:50,411 --> 00:07:53,896
Things change and sometimes it's for the better and sometimes it's for the worse.

65
00:07:54,437 --> 00:08:04,312
They don't go deeply into the problems that arise when we don't actually change our lives through the insight into impermanence.

66
00:08:04,293 --> 00:08:10,439
So when we see something is impermanent, the natural thing is not to get attached to it.

67
00:08:11,319 --> 00:08:32,038
So immediately, every time you have something which you treasure, it might be a ring, it might be a precious vase or whatever it is, or it might be something of a deeper value, a relationship, something like your work that you treasure.

68
00:08:32,895 --> 00:08:37,304
it's good practice to say, well, you know, this too will come to an end.

69
00:08:37,826 --> 00:08:39,009
See, this too will come to an end.

70
00:08:39,350 --> 00:08:42,856
Now, you might think that would send you into a depression.

71
00:08:43,357 --> 00:08:45,302
Well, it might.

72
00:08:45,923 --> 00:08:51,788
But the point is to be ready for what is inevitably going to happen because all things come to an end.

73
00:08:52,509 --> 00:09:02,480
So seeing a Nietzsche as something which is impermanent is about forming a different relationship to the world.

74
00:09:02,500 --> 00:09:09,628
It's about really recognizing that whatever we have or possess is going to change.

75
00:09:09,668 --> 00:09:11,110
It's going to disappear at some point.

76
00:09:11,951 --> 00:09:13,331
It's not going to be there for us.

77
00:09:14,662 --> 00:09:16,865
So that's the first thing.

78
00:09:17,285 --> 00:09:28,225
And because we see that when we attach to something and we don't see impermanence, then we also see that in fact this is the cause of suffering.

79
00:09:28,245 --> 00:09:36,879
So anicca there, this impermanence, guides us into seeing suffering from the angle of impermanence.

80
00:09:38,322 --> 00:09:40,365
So that's one way of looking at things.

81
00:09:40,986 --> 00:09:48,852
And the way we undermine that is by constantly reminding ourselves that things arise and pass away.

82
00:09:50,302 --> 00:09:55,509
And the biggest arising and passing away, of course, is being born and then having to die.

83
00:09:56,291 --> 00:10:08,250
So the actual contemplation of death is really a very strong contemplation, which at first might seem a bit lugubrious.

84
00:10:08,309 --> 00:10:11,635
It might drive you into jumping off a bridge.

85
00:10:12,115 --> 00:10:16,984
But actually what it does is it puts your life into a certain balance.

86
00:10:16,964 --> 00:10:30,923
Because recognizing that life comes to an end, because of our aim in life, which is to become liberated, it makes this present moment that much more precious.

87
00:10:31,357 --> 00:10:38,932
If you think that death's going to happen sometime in the vast future, then of course there's no sense of immediacy.

88
00:10:39,052 --> 00:10:43,500
There's no sense of sanvega, that sense of urgency in our practice.

89
00:10:43,519 --> 00:10:52,775
So by reminding ourselves that we are one breath away from death, we are one heartbeat away from death.

90
00:10:52,917 --> 00:10:53,738
It's not very far, is it?

91
00:10:54,325 --> 00:10:56,408
One heartbeat.

92
00:10:56,427 --> 00:10:57,149
Boom, boom.

93
00:10:57,168 --> 00:10:57,568
That's it.

94
00:10:57,649 --> 00:10:57,950
Finished.

95
00:10:58,190 --> 00:10:58,409
Gone.

96
00:10:58,890 --> 00:10:59,071
See?

97
00:10:59,471 --> 00:11:18,135
By reminding ourselves that we're on this knife edge, that life can end at any time, we begin to experience life as much more bright, much more alert, because we're actually making it, we actually try to make it more meaningful for ourselves.

98
00:11:18,155 --> 00:11:20,940
And that's, of course, where the spiritual practice comes in.

99
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:34,975
So really looking at impermanence in all its different facets, both in the sense that in the minutest moments, I mean, how long does a moment last?

100
00:11:37,538 --> 00:11:39,080
How long can you hold a moment?

101
00:11:41,302 --> 00:11:42,945
It's like, how long is it?

102
00:11:45,034 --> 00:11:47,378
Gone, isn't it?

103
00:11:47,658 --> 00:11:51,443
And yet the mind is able to create this continuity for us.

104
00:11:51,825 --> 00:11:53,126
I mean, think about music.

105
00:11:53,707 --> 00:11:57,373
You only hear one note, but somehow we can hear the whole tune.

106
00:11:58,033 --> 00:12:05,765
Somehow we capture the whole tune as it's going along and think that we're actually hearing the whole piece.

107
00:12:06,285 --> 00:12:08,089
But actually it's only one note at a time.

108
00:12:09,942 --> 00:12:20,695
So there's the ability of the mind to contain some idea of continuity, without which you couldn't live in the world, for heaven's sake.

109
00:12:20,875 --> 00:12:23,899
You'd be waking up everywhere you were.

110
00:12:24,340 --> 00:12:30,488
So there has to be that quality of continuity in our ordinary lives.

111
00:12:30,508 --> 00:12:34,192
But we're fooled by it into thinking that's the way things are.

112
00:12:34,793 --> 00:12:35,494
That's the problem.

113
00:12:37,769 --> 00:12:52,229
So even in the minute, even in the minuscule layer of each moment arising and passing away, we can begin to catch the insecurity of our lives.

114
00:12:53,610 --> 00:12:57,836
And it's living with that insecurity which sharpens the present moment.

115
00:12:59,234 --> 00:13:08,169
And then in the long term, that contemplation every so often, that the end of life is this full stop at the end.

116
00:13:08,210 --> 00:13:17,046
And to know that that's going to come, that also puts a pressure on us to make sense of this present moment, not to waste it, not to get lazy.

117
00:13:19,090 --> 00:13:22,355
Don't be lazy now and be remorseful afterwards, says the Buddha.

118
00:13:24,142 --> 00:13:33,097
And remember that I mentioned, I think, earlier in the week, Sun Lung, this fierce Arahant, who when asked, why is it people don't become liberated as quick as him, he said, because they're lazy.

119
00:13:34,660 --> 00:13:38,668
And we're lazy because we think that our lives are just going to carry on.

120
00:13:38,687 --> 00:13:41,331
I mean, what's the problem?

121
00:13:41,351 --> 00:13:48,445
In the East, where the idea of rebirth is very easy for people, it's just part and parcel of their culture,

122
00:13:49,859 --> 00:13:52,865
then you do get this sort of laziness.

123
00:13:53,326 --> 00:13:56,171
When you ask them, are you working to become liberated?

124
00:13:56,532 --> 00:14:01,923
No, I'm building up my bank account of good deeds and virtue and all that.

125
00:14:02,443 --> 00:14:04,748
And I'll be there when the next Buddha comes.

126
00:14:06,171 --> 00:14:08,796
Like, when's that, you know?

127
00:14:10,496 --> 00:14:15,743
And of course, when the next Buddha comes, they'll be there still getting in their virtue and building up their good deeds.

128
00:14:16,543 --> 00:14:26,274
So sometimes to believe that life goes on in this sort of rebirthing process really makes a person lazy.

129
00:14:28,096 --> 00:14:38,648
So to bring about this sense of urgency that the Buddha talks about, that recollection of death is a very strong...

130
00:14:39,538 --> 00:14:40,691
Very strong practice.

131
00:14:41,091 --> 00:14:44,134
And it's right there in the discourse on how to establish right awareness.

132
00:14:44,895 --> 00:14:50,741
I mean, there he describes, I think it's 13 states of a corpse rotting on the charnel ground.

133
00:14:50,761 --> 00:14:55,386
So in those days, they would leave the corpse out to be eaten by vultures and wild animals.

134
00:14:56,128 --> 00:15:06,698
And monks were instructed, it was the general practice of the day, it was part of the self-mortification, to go out there and watch corpses slowly corrupt and disappear into dust, you see.

135
00:15:07,318 --> 00:15:08,360
The commentaries are very helpful.

136
00:15:08,380 --> 00:15:09,782
They tell you not to sit windward.

137
00:15:13,153 --> 00:15:40,578
so I mean unfortunately we can't do that these days but interestingly enough if you're a monastic and you go to the east Thailand Sri Lanka Burma the hospitals will let you in to see an autopsy and that's always quite an interesting thing to see because if you haven't most people haven't seen a dead body you know most people haven't felt a dead body you know and it's quite an experience to actually see one and to and

138
00:15:40,828 --> 00:15:44,953
and to catch its lifelessness, and how the mind wants to give it life.

139
00:15:45,914 --> 00:15:54,284
You look at the face of a corpse, and it's as though the mind wants to give it some sort of expression, some sort of movement, but it just won't.

140
00:15:54,304 --> 00:15:54,884
It's dead.

141
00:15:57,187 --> 00:16:03,174
So there was a lovely story, while I'm on about it, about this, he's a Westerner,

142
00:16:03,408 --> 00:16:05,591
And he went to Sri Lanka, became a monastic.

143
00:16:06,152 --> 00:16:09,817
And he wanted to do this death meditation as the Buddha described it.

144
00:16:10,357 --> 00:16:18,811
So somehow he got the permission to get the body of a corpse of a convict, somebody in prison who died in prison.

145
00:16:19,932 --> 00:16:21,235
Somehow he got permission to do this.

146
00:16:21,554 --> 00:16:26,562
And he carried this corpse on his back to where he was living in this cave.

147
00:16:27,183 --> 00:16:30,788
And there he built a cage, a glass cage with a funnel.

148
00:16:31,250 --> 00:16:32,672
And he put the body in it.

149
00:16:32,904 --> 00:16:35,629
And he observed the rotting of the body.

150
00:16:36,509 --> 00:16:42,438
Well, when the newspapers heard about this, they declaimed, finally, a real monk.

151
00:16:45,243 --> 00:16:47,567
Finally, we've got somebody who can really look at this.

152
00:16:48,467 --> 00:16:54,056
Anyway, as the story ends, he finally left the order and went off to help Mother Teresa in Calcutta, I think.

153
00:16:55,538 --> 00:16:57,782
So I think it must have done something for him.

154
00:16:59,668 --> 00:17:01,591
That's a bit extreme, of course.

155
00:17:01,951 --> 00:17:02,852
We needn't do that.

156
00:17:03,854 --> 00:17:08,000
Just contemplating our own death is often enough.

157
00:17:09,340 --> 00:17:20,154
And every so often when you wake up with a pain that you haven't had before, or during the day with a pain, just watch that fear that comes, the fear of death.

158
00:17:20,895 --> 00:17:27,364
So it's just something that you can bring in just as a small daily practice, you see.

159
00:17:27,344 --> 00:17:40,701
These practices, the vipassana, the metta, the contemplations that we do in the evening about sickness, aging and death, it's just this constant little reminder every day that works.

160
00:17:41,122 --> 00:17:46,209
And it doesn't take a second, it doesn't take any time, it's just that little reminder every day.

161
00:17:46,249 --> 00:17:51,174
And it very slowly changes our attitude to the way we're living.

162
00:17:54,277 --> 00:18:05,513
Now the other side of anicca, so one part of anicca guides us into the dukkha, the suffering, and the other side, of course, is because it's impermanent, it takes away any sense of substantiality.

163
00:18:05,815 --> 00:18:09,480
So it takes us into the anatta teaching about not-self.

164
00:18:10,281 --> 00:18:22,359
So starting with anicca, it's a sort of perspective into the other two, into the suffering or the unsatisfactoriness and into the not-self.

165
00:18:22,339 --> 00:18:26,172
But each of these, of course, have their own particular viewpoints.

166
00:18:27,075 --> 00:18:32,873
And when it comes to dukkha, the Buddha then expresses that through dependent origination.

167
00:18:34,844 --> 00:18:48,567
And independent origination, he points very clearly at two places where this whole dukkha rests, the whole problem of unsatisfactoriness rests.

168
00:18:48,586 --> 00:18:54,777
And he starts off by that avijja, that not knowing, not knowing.

169
00:18:54,757 --> 00:19:05,612
So it's through not knowing that we make a mistake and we form a wrong relationship with this psychophysical organism, this human being.

170
00:19:06,512 --> 00:19:11,519
And if you think about it, it's understandable.

171
00:19:11,941 --> 00:19:13,762
Because when we're born, what do we know?

172
00:19:14,263 --> 00:19:16,046
And you just find yourself in this body.

173
00:19:16,146 --> 00:19:17,028
You are this body.

174
00:19:17,669 --> 00:19:21,954
And it's quite understandable that we should think that this is what we are.

175
00:19:22,715 --> 00:19:23,717
And we end up

176
00:19:24,153 --> 00:19:25,596
Living with that delusion.

177
00:19:25,958 --> 00:19:31,952
Now, because of that, we try to seek happiness in this form.

178
00:19:32,714 --> 00:19:37,507
Now, that's the driving force, is it not, of our life?

179
00:19:37,827 --> 00:19:38,871
To seek happiness.

180
00:19:39,471 --> 00:19:40,575
Isn't that the driving force?

181
00:19:42,901 --> 00:19:45,346
Happiness in however you wish to define it.

182
00:19:45,928 --> 00:19:54,465
So some people might define it as a wonderful relationship, others riches, others fame, others lots of money, others all of that.

183
00:19:54,486 --> 00:19:54,767
You see?

184
00:19:55,067 --> 00:19:57,412
So it depends on how you define your happiness.

185
00:19:57,633 --> 00:19:58,654
That's what you're chasing.

186
00:19:59,356 --> 00:19:59,457
Okay?

187
00:19:59,477 --> 00:19:59,576
Okay?

188
00:20:04,348 --> 00:20:13,566
And seeking some sort of permanent happy state in the human form always lets us down.

189
00:20:13,967 --> 00:20:24,645
It lets us down, A, because it's impermanent, but the attachment itself has its own consequence of suffering, which we've been through, especially around pleasure.

190
00:20:25,448 --> 00:20:27,791
So remember, what happens is...

191
00:20:29,694 --> 00:20:34,220
we form our happinesses around things that we collect.

192
00:20:35,020 --> 00:20:39,965
These things can be the money, it can be fame, it can be power, it can be people.

193
00:20:40,467 --> 00:20:42,769
It doesn't matter what it is, we collect them.

194
00:20:43,210 --> 00:20:52,140
And the more we collect of these happinesses, the more we feel safe, the more we feel secure, and the more we feel happy.

195
00:20:53,540 --> 00:20:59,027
A person feels much more happy if they have a billion pound in the bank than if they have

196
00:20:59,597 --> 00:21:00,878
One million pounds in the bank.

197
00:21:02,181 --> 00:21:05,564
Your happiness grows with the amount of money you've got.

198
00:21:05,584 --> 00:21:13,432
So these happinesses are an accumulation of things.

199
00:21:16,095 --> 00:21:20,439
This accumulation now has to be guarded.

200
00:21:21,820 --> 00:21:23,201
Other people want what you have.

201
00:21:24,163 --> 00:21:26,144
Other people want your billion pounds for a start.

202
00:21:27,593 --> 00:21:33,039
And anybody that undermines this happiness must be annihilated as quickly as possible.

203
00:21:34,021 --> 00:21:39,208
So there you've got your aversion, which is pushing away anything which is undermining you.

204
00:21:39,969 --> 00:21:44,796
And if what is undermining you is too big to handle, then you've got to run for it.

205
00:21:44,816 --> 00:21:51,585
So there you have your three basic attitudes that arise out of this wrong relationship.

206
00:21:52,165 --> 00:21:55,390
Acquisitiveness, aversion and fear.

207
00:21:58,086 --> 00:22:02,792
And once we've got those attitudes, we start acting upon them.

208
00:22:03,574 --> 00:22:09,040
That produces unwholesome actions, which themselves have unwholesome consequences.

209
00:22:10,262 --> 00:22:17,932
Because it all demands that the world be moved and shifted in order to satisfy my happiness.

210
00:22:20,175 --> 00:22:28,026
So from a delusive point of view, I'm constantly manipulating the world so that I can feel comfortable, I can feel happy.

211
00:22:28,968 --> 00:22:35,240
So I'm in constant conflict with the world, except in those small moments when I've finally got it.

212
00:22:36,761 --> 00:22:42,333
And then it lasts, what, a couple of seconds, a few days at most, and it's gone.

213
00:22:42,854 --> 00:22:46,200
And then I'm back on the trail again of trying to get this happiness.

214
00:22:49,353 --> 00:23:08,262
This manifests as this tanha, this special word that the Buddha uses, which we translate as craving, which is far too strong because it doesn't include the little small attachments, the little small attachments that we have, the small little selfishness.

215
00:23:08,644 --> 00:23:10,867
I'm just taking that big piece of cake.

216
00:23:11,509 --> 00:23:13,531
Everybody else takes the little one.

217
00:23:13,551 --> 00:23:14,212
And then...

218
00:23:15,374 --> 00:23:24,886
And so it's that whole area of grasping, wanting, needing in that psychological sense.

219
00:23:24,906 --> 00:23:26,328
That's the attachment.

220
00:23:26,650 --> 00:23:32,336
So wherever there's attachment, there's a psychological dependency on it for happiness.

221
00:23:33,077 --> 00:23:39,527
When we describe that happiness, when we say, well, what do I mean when I say I am happy?

222
00:23:39,827 --> 00:23:43,692
I think you'll agree with me when I say we're talking about a mental state.

223
00:23:44,990 --> 00:23:53,559
If I put pleasant food in my mouth but it doesn't make me happy, then I just spit it out and try another dish.

224
00:23:55,563 --> 00:23:57,846
I'm looking to food to make me happy.

225
00:23:58,125 --> 00:24:00,588
I'm looking to a relationship to make me happy.

226
00:24:02,090 --> 00:24:09,579
And this happiness always defines a mental state, mainly the emotional content of that mental state.

227
00:24:12,968 --> 00:24:15,993
It's never the object itself which is happiness.

228
00:24:17,135 --> 00:24:29,019
It may be the proximate cause of the happiness, in other words, something that I'm dependent on, but what I'm really trying to do is to create a happy state within myself.

229
00:24:31,243 --> 00:24:52,932
Now, that's when the seeing of anicca comes in, because when you realize that these happiness states are not under your control, that you can bring them up under certain circumstances, but that they just change whether you want them to or not, and sometimes the same circumstance that made you happy then doesn't make you happy now.

230
00:24:53,512 --> 00:24:56,896
So we're constantly, as drug addicts say, chasing the dragon.

231
00:24:59,087 --> 00:25:00,770
And that's the point of tanha.

232
00:25:00,790 --> 00:25:17,035
So what the Buddha's pointing to is, A, there's a profound misunderstanding underneath our lives, and it manifests as this form of greed, aversion and fear.

233
00:25:18,217 --> 00:25:23,023
And the consequence of that is, of course, guilt, shame, remorse, etc., etc.

234
00:25:24,105 --> 00:25:28,031
And if you don't have guilt, shame or remorse, then you end up being callous, hard,

235
00:25:28,416 --> 00:25:29,981
unfeeling, unforgiving.

236
00:25:32,208 --> 00:25:38,105
So here, what he's describing is the psychology which is causing us problems.

237
00:25:38,373 --> 00:25:56,933
this fundamental misunderstanding as to who we are, and therefore we seek happiness in the phenomenal world, that is the world of the psychophysical organism, we'll come to that in a minute, and that manifests through this word, this tanha.

238
00:25:57,654 --> 00:26:04,583
So in our meditation, what we're trying to do is constantly to separate out

239
00:26:04,798 --> 00:26:08,480
the given from the reaction.

240
00:26:08,663 --> 00:26:13,550
And that's the process of seeing how we create suffering for ourselves.

241
00:26:14,251 --> 00:26:19,319
So the given might be a pleasant mental state, some sort of memory.

242
00:26:19,901 --> 00:26:21,824
This is in our meditation here and now.

243
00:26:22,345 --> 00:26:29,435
It could be something that we went out in nature and it gives us pleasure and it gives us a certain pleasurable feeling.

244
00:26:29,936 --> 00:26:33,462
And what we are catching is how we're relating to that.

245
00:26:34,364 --> 00:26:35,987
How we're relating to that.

246
00:26:36,457 --> 00:26:43,123
and how when it doesn't satisfy us there's a feeling of disappointment or a feeling of boredom.

247
00:26:43,544 --> 00:26:51,510
So there's a whole sort of psychology around the relationship we have with the world that we experience.

248
00:26:51,530 --> 00:27:04,624
And it's catching that and then of course the practice of not joining in, not actually identifying with it, to be able to name it and to know it and not to identify with it.

249
00:27:04,891 --> 00:27:12,488
And very slowly this relationship changes, away from that wanting to manipulate the world,

250
00:27:13,413 --> 00:27:22,000
moving towards this is the way it is, that sort of radical, straightforward acceptance of each and every moment as it arises.

251
00:27:22,801 --> 00:27:29,669
There's an undermining of wanting to push away the unpleasant, but of accepting it.

252
00:27:31,391 --> 00:27:41,039
When I was at Kandaboda in the monastery there, I was in the back end of the monastery in my own kuti, my own hut.

253
00:27:42,353 --> 00:27:47,161
And there was a block of rooms not so far from me.

254
00:27:47,701 --> 00:27:48,884
I could see them through the trees.

255
00:27:49,505 --> 00:27:54,772
Maybe about, I don't know, 30 metres or so.

256
00:27:54,792 --> 00:27:58,298
And foreigners would come into that.

257
00:27:58,358 --> 00:27:59,401
Not singlees.

258
00:27:59,441 --> 00:28:01,324
It was actually built for foreigners.

259
00:28:02,012 --> 00:28:06,359
And so there'd be this constant change of people coming in and coming out.

260
00:28:06,961 --> 00:28:10,586
Some of them, of course, were very serious meditators, utterly committed.

261
00:28:10,946 --> 00:28:15,614
But some of them were absolute... Well, prats, for want of a better word.

262
00:28:18,438 --> 00:28:19,599
And...

263
00:28:19,968 --> 00:28:23,978
They used to complain to the abbot, you know, and say, well, you know, he's doing this.

264
00:28:24,218 --> 00:28:25,540
This was the male section.

265
00:28:25,580 --> 00:28:29,069
The female section, I didn't know anything about because there's a wall around it.

266
00:28:29,109 --> 00:28:34,201
And they would go to the abbot and say, he's doing this and he's doing that.

267
00:28:35,064 --> 00:28:36,728
And the abbot would never do anything.

268
00:28:36,708 --> 00:28:40,977
And there was one point where we had this self-professed schizophrenic.

269
00:28:41,959 --> 00:28:47,770
And he would sit out there in the nude, and sometimes he'd jump up and jump around and dance.

270
00:28:48,231 --> 00:28:49,394
It was an absolute riot.

271
00:28:50,195 --> 00:28:54,345
And eventually, I felt that this was just...

272
00:28:54,510 --> 00:28:57,516
You know, a bit beyond the pale, you know what I mean?

273
00:28:57,536 --> 00:29:00,580
A little bit of disturbance, fine, you accept this and all that.

274
00:29:00,601 --> 00:29:07,972
So I went to see the abbot thinking that I would have this great authority as a monk rather than a layperson.

275
00:29:07,992 --> 00:29:12,519
And I explained to him that, you know, this was very injurious to the whole practice and it was messing people up.

276
00:29:13,444 --> 00:29:15,048
But he did nothing, you see.

277
00:29:15,067 --> 00:29:16,128
He did nothing at all, you see.

278
00:29:16,630 --> 00:29:19,234
And I went back and I thought, hmm, it's very interesting.

279
00:29:19,895 --> 00:29:24,242
And then I realised, of course, that that's what we're constantly doing.

280
00:29:24,663 --> 00:29:33,478
Whenever something which disturbs us comes, especially when something is, shall we say...

281
00:29:34,048 --> 00:29:44,045
evil, perhaps that's too strong a word, when we see something as dangerous or we find somebody who threatens us, our attitude is to move away.

282
00:29:44,105 --> 00:29:50,775
And that, of course, allows the person to have full reign of the situation.

283
00:29:51,598 --> 00:30:02,412
Whereas what the teaching was to me was, yes, there is this disturbance and at some point or other it will go and you stay with it.

284
00:30:03,292 --> 00:30:04,074
And that's what happened.

285
00:30:04,434 --> 00:30:05,135
He disappeared.

286
00:30:05,675 --> 00:30:07,679
He went one day and he never came back.

287
00:30:10,521 --> 00:30:18,332
And if you take that on a political level, you see how important it is that when something happens in a country where there's some

288
00:30:19,307 --> 00:30:24,601
There's some manifestation of some real wrong thinking, some evil.

289
00:30:25,403 --> 00:30:33,282
The good people tend to shy away, tend to go away, instead of staying there and working with it and eventually undermining it.

290
00:30:34,174 --> 00:30:45,394
So this whole idea about delusion manifests in many, many sort of subtle ways in our lives.

291
00:30:45,855 --> 00:30:54,528
Always remember trying to manipulate the present moment or doing something about the present moment to make ourselves feel comfortable or at best happy.

292
00:30:55,031 --> 00:31:07,049
And it's catching that, it's catching that, you see, and then allowing the wisdom to arise, which is, given this situation, what ought to be done from a truly ethical point of view.

293
00:31:08,673 --> 00:31:13,099
And that undermines this wrong understanding, you see.

294
00:31:13,721 --> 00:31:18,788
As it were, it drops downwards through the process to the whole idea of me.

295
00:31:21,451 --> 00:31:21,833
When...

296
00:31:22,353 --> 00:31:28,460
In those happy hippie days, people used to go around saying, I do my own thing in my own way, in my own time.

297
00:31:29,560 --> 00:31:36,088
That was the greatest expression of Western individualism you could get.

298
00:31:36,548 --> 00:31:37,671
To hell with the world.

299
00:31:37,691 --> 00:31:41,816
I will do my own thing in my own way, in my own time.

300
00:31:41,855 --> 00:31:45,058
Forget the rest of you.

301
00:31:45,339 --> 00:31:47,382
I'm the one who's important here.

302
00:31:49,403 --> 00:32:07,428
And that process of constantly letting go of attachment, of constantly working with the unpleasant, of constantly not trying to manipulate the present, you see, is undermining this sense of an isolated self.

303
00:32:08,229 --> 00:32:11,913
And that's when you begin to make connections with the world around you.

304
00:32:12,095 --> 00:32:15,259
That's when you begin to...

305
00:32:16,453 --> 00:32:25,733
begin to establish a different relationship, not based on this very solid idea of a self or an ego.

306
00:32:27,577 --> 00:32:34,732
So for instance, when the Buddha visits these three monks who happen to be fully liberated, he calls them the Anurudas, I think.

307
00:32:35,134 --> 00:32:39,561
He says to the chief monk, he says, how is it you live peacefully together?

308
00:32:40,163 --> 00:32:49,257
He said, well, every morning we say to ourselves, what if I put aside what I want to do and do what the others want to do?

309
00:32:50,819 --> 00:32:54,184
That's not quite, I do my own thing in my own way in my own time.

310
00:32:54,846 --> 00:33:02,678
And in any group of people, of course, everybody has to say that or else it doesn't work because you just get abused.

311
00:33:04,278 --> 00:33:16,772
But if that was our attitude, you can see how we begin to feel much more at ease with life, by asking the people around us, what do they want to do?

312
00:33:17,594 --> 00:33:21,999
And not just going into a situation and saying, well, this is the way I want it to be.

313
00:33:24,382 --> 00:33:30,048
So this whole area of dukkha, of unsatisfactoriness,

314
00:33:31,143 --> 00:33:51,784
has to do with both the acquisitiveness, which we've been looking at through the eating process, through trying to enjoy life with that override of indulgence, which simply means attachment and trying to create a beautiful mental state by stuffing ourselves.

315
00:33:51,950 --> 00:34:05,353
And the other side of it is the actual suffering, the bit where we become averse, where we become fearful, anxious, where it gets on top of us and we get depressed, etc., etc.

316
00:34:05,633 --> 00:34:12,625
All that belongs to this deep, profound, wrong relationship we have with this psychophysical organism.

317
00:34:16,132 --> 00:34:26,751
So now, when we begin to understand this, we move to that slightly deeper level of not-self, not-me, not-mine.

318
00:34:27,474 --> 00:34:35,389
And what we're doing here is we are beginning to disidentify with this psychophysical organism.

319
00:34:35,369 --> 00:34:55,052
So when we're sitting in meditation and we're using these little noting words, and especially if you preface them with their, so there's pain, there's unhappiness, there's sadness, there's joy, whatever it is, what we're doing is we're pushing it away from ourselves.

320
00:34:55,393 --> 00:34:58,036
We're disidentifying.

321
00:34:59,438 --> 00:35:02,101
Just very quickly, if we go back to when we were born,

322
00:35:02,858 --> 00:35:11,726
There's a woman called Margaret Mahler who was a student of Freud and she studied babies up to about the age of three.

323
00:35:12,126 --> 00:35:25,358
And what she discovered was that for the first three or four months all there is is this blanket of sensation, an undifferentiated sensation, except that some were painful and some were pleasant.

324
00:35:26,659 --> 00:35:32,224
And then slowly out of four months there looms your first object, usually your carer, your mother.

325
00:35:33,418 --> 00:35:38,731
And very slowly the baby pushes the world out, creates a 3D world.

326
00:35:39,032 --> 00:35:42,481
That seems to be what's happening when they're reaching out for rattles and stuff.

327
00:35:42,782 --> 00:35:44,507
They're actually creating that world.

328
00:35:45,309 --> 00:35:47,454
So it's not as though we're born with that.

329
00:35:47,675 --> 00:35:50,702
We're born with the potential of creating that.

330
00:35:50,681 --> 00:35:53,585
phenomenal world, but it has to be developed.

331
00:35:54,144 --> 00:36:02,612
And it's not until the age of three, thereabouts, two and a half, three, that the child says, I am a boy, I am a girl, and everything else isn't me.

332
00:36:02,632 --> 00:36:03,474
It's taken three years.

333
00:36:04,213 --> 00:36:08,297
Now, what we're doing is, we are taking that process inwardly.

334
00:36:08,697 --> 00:36:16,885
We're separating out of this person that we've made, you see, and what constitutes the person.

335
00:36:17,065 --> 00:36:20,688
The person is made up of the body, the image of the body,

336
00:36:20,668 --> 00:36:24,635
of the pleasures and the pain that the body gives us.

337
00:36:24,655 --> 00:36:33,106
The person is made of these emotions and our habits and our thought patterns and all our conditioning.

338
00:36:33,768 --> 00:36:38,034
All that is then put into this concept of a person.

339
00:36:38,173 --> 00:36:39,335
This is me.

340
00:36:39,856 --> 00:36:57,693
And by sitting and finding this observation post within ourselves, this place where we can observe and feel things, what we're actually doing is exactly what the baby did with that two-dimensional world, creating a three-dimensional world, creating itself away from there.

341
00:36:58,315 --> 00:37:08,445
We are beginning to isolate this awareness from everything that it's aware of.

342
00:37:09,302 --> 00:37:11,938
And that is the process of liberation.

343
00:37:12,728 --> 00:37:24,798
The process of liberation is both this liberating ourselves from the wrong desire of things, the wrong attachment to things, but at this deep level it's disidentification.

344
00:37:25,278 --> 00:37:40,152
So we relocate ourselves backwards until we reach this self-awareness, this observer, the feeler, the witness, the one who knows.

345
00:37:42,563 --> 00:37:52,735
And every time we fall into the old habit of becoming this other self, right, then that's the point where we have to jump out and recognize the mistake we've made.

346
00:37:53,416 --> 00:38:01,827
So when you have a pain, sort of a headache, and you say, oh, I've got a headache, so you stop and say, hold on, no, no, there is a headache.

347
00:38:04,431 --> 00:38:09,177
Every time you have an emotion, you say, oh, I feel so depressed, I feel so anxious, you say,

348
00:38:09,360 --> 00:38:12,876
Ah, no, there's depression, there's anxiety.

349
00:38:13,318 --> 00:38:19,405
So that's a constant practice that we have to take in our daily lives, constantly separating out.

350
00:38:20,228 --> 00:38:48,581
but remember that that's also a false position because here we have this new self it's another self who is disidentifying with everything and there's a danger there that you become so disidentified with it that you're no longer engaged so that itself is not a pleasant place to be so you still have to go into the psychophysical organism but you go in with right intention

351
00:38:50,418 --> 00:39:16,391
and it's that ability to go in with right intention that reinforces the wisdom that you get from that disidentifying in other words through disidentifying you're undermining all those consequences of delusion which is the greed, the fear, the aversion and by going in with right intention

352
00:39:16,675 --> 00:39:34,818
And becoming your action, being your actions, your thoughts, your wholesome thoughts, your wholesome speech, your skillful actions, you're actually reinforcing and manifesting and reinforcing your right understanding of the way things are.

353
00:39:34,798 --> 00:39:40,150
And that manifests always as some shade of the four illimitables.

354
00:39:40,851 --> 00:39:46,885
Love, which is that basic connection, compassion, joy and peacefulness or equanimity.

355
00:39:50,054 --> 00:39:57,186
Now remember that that position of the self in the observer is also a false position.

356
00:39:58,007 --> 00:40:01,353
Because there's two people there, there's two things there rather.

357
00:40:01,512 --> 00:40:04,257
There's the observing and there's the observing of the self.

358
00:40:05,039 --> 00:40:06,260
Self-awareness.

359
00:40:06,460 --> 00:40:07,963
So you can't be that either.

360
00:40:08,505 --> 00:40:11,590
You can't be the object that you're aware of.

361
00:40:11,570 --> 00:40:15,597
But unfortunately, you can't get beyond that state by an act of will.

362
00:40:16,219 --> 00:40:17,440
You can get beyond the body.

363
00:40:17,740 --> 00:40:25,715
As soon as we know that, as soon as I look at something or feel something as an object, I've disidentified with it.

364
00:40:26,177 --> 00:40:28,802
And you can do it with an emotion rather than just becoming it.

365
00:40:28,782 --> 00:40:32,532
Rather than just being angry, you can say, there is anger.

366
00:40:32,974 --> 00:40:34,117
And we can do it with images.

367
00:40:34,778 --> 00:40:36,945
Thoughts are more difficult because they're so fast.

368
00:40:37,144 --> 00:40:43,804
But when we're highly concentrated, well, when we've got a decent, you know, steady concentration...

369
00:40:43,784 --> 00:40:45,126
You can catch thoughts coming.

370
00:40:45,186 --> 00:40:48,231
Sometimes they're like neon lights in front of you.

371
00:40:49,271 --> 00:40:56,483
And that's this constant pulling away, re-establishing an inner sense of self, this self-observer.

372
00:40:56,503 --> 00:40:58,905
But you can't get rid of that image.

373
00:40:59,367 --> 00:41:00,528
You can't get rid of the self.

374
00:41:01,309 --> 00:41:08,780
Because that's an image of the knowing in the mirror of the mind.

375
00:41:10,322 --> 00:41:13,166
It's like when you look in a mirror, you can't get rid of that face.

376
00:41:14,699 --> 00:41:17,061
Every time you look in a mirror, it's there.

377
00:41:17,101 --> 00:41:18,161
See?

378
00:41:20,585 --> 00:41:28,271
Now, the unfortunate thing is, I think most people think, that when they look in the mirror and they see their face, they think that's the way people see them.

379
00:41:28,291 --> 00:41:35,639
But it's a great horror and shock when they actually use the second mirror to see this mirror image.

380
00:41:35,679 --> 00:41:36,780
Because remember, it's turned round.

381
00:41:37,340 --> 00:41:40,242
That's why if you put writing up in the mirror, you can't read it.

382
00:41:40,262 --> 00:41:41,184
It's the other way round, you see?

383
00:41:41,905 --> 00:41:44,487
And it comes as a great shock to know how big your nose really is.

384
00:41:45,242 --> 00:41:46,804
See?

385
00:41:46,824 --> 00:41:50,067
And it's the same when you hear your voice first recorded.

386
00:41:50,086 --> 00:41:52,349
You know, God, I don't sound like that.

387
00:41:52,369 --> 00:41:53,451
Or worse, when you're videoed.

388
00:41:55,172 --> 00:41:57,054
I didn't think you were behaving like that.

389
00:41:57,074 --> 00:42:03,280
Anyway, so it's beginning to recognize that that is an image, you see.

390
00:42:03,519 --> 00:42:14,489
So now, when everything is absolutely quiet, when everything is really, really still, and I've been saying this to a few of you, you know, turn that gaze inward towards the knowing.

391
00:42:15,280 --> 00:42:21,505
Turn the gaze inwards towards the knowing and ask yourself afterwards, what is the knowing made of?

392
00:42:21,786 --> 00:42:25,929
What's constituted?

393
00:42:26,411 --> 00:42:27,391
What constitutes it?

394
00:42:27,692 --> 00:42:38,322
So for instance, when we go into pain and we go into what constitutes pain, we might find tightness or heat and all those sorts of things.

395
00:42:38,621 --> 00:42:43,887
So now we know that that's the reality of the situation, inverted commas.

396
00:42:43,867 --> 00:42:45,329
that there is sensation.

397
00:42:45,528 --> 00:42:46,911
Pain is a mental construct.

398
00:42:47,391 --> 00:42:53,760
So this sense of self, you see, it is telling us something about our true nature.

399
00:42:57,204 --> 00:43:07,817
And it's that sort of investigation that begins to undermine this really, really deep and basic mistake we've made about identity.

400
00:43:09,278 --> 00:43:11,561
And in that vein...

401
00:43:12,992 --> 00:43:15,737
The Buddha states quite clearly that mind is foremost.

402
00:43:16,398 --> 00:43:19,344
Mind is there right at the beginning and it's there right at the end.

403
00:43:19,425 --> 00:43:20,666
It's the most important thing.

404
00:43:21,027 --> 00:43:22,811
Now just consider for a minute, you see.

405
00:43:23,934 --> 00:43:25,657
Photons are coming into our eyes.

406
00:43:29,083 --> 00:43:30,806
Pressure waves are hitting the ear.

407
00:43:31,889 --> 00:43:35,355
But these are actually quite minimal information.

408
00:43:35,639 --> 00:43:44,130
When you see diagrams of what happens to a person's eye when they look at a picture, it's going all over the place.

409
00:43:44,811 --> 00:43:48,255
But the actual viewer of the picture still sees the picture as a whole.

410
00:43:49,398 --> 00:43:53,884
But the eye is actually moving at this tremendous speed, picking up little pixels here and there.

411
00:43:55,248 --> 00:44:03,864
So we have these sense bases which are sensitive to certain data, to certain information, but the information is quite minimal.

412
00:44:04,586 --> 00:44:13,324
And what the mind does is it takes it into what's known as, in Buddhism, the inner sense door, the mind door, and there it's filled out.

413
00:44:13,304 --> 00:44:21,878
And I read somewhere that actually what happens in the eye is that this filling out is then put back onto the retina.

414
00:44:22,018 --> 00:44:26,605
So it gives us a real picture, inverted commas.

415
00:44:28,067 --> 00:44:33,014
So there's a whole thing going on inside this complex of the brain and mind.

416
00:44:33,335 --> 00:44:37,842
And what we end up with is the world that we've actually created.

417
00:44:39,358 --> 00:44:41,722
That is the phenomenal world, you see.

418
00:44:42,461 --> 00:44:47,588
And it's beginning to recognize that that isn't an objective thing.

419
00:44:48,027 --> 00:44:50,731
That is something that we are actually creating all the time.

420
00:44:51,050 --> 00:45:03,864
So that even though we would all agree that this room exists, in the sense that when we all leave, it doesn't disappear, the fact is there are as many rooms here as there are people, in terms of experience of it.

421
00:45:04,958 --> 00:45:16,297
So now, grasping that, that the world I'm living in is being manufactured by me, part of it is given, both the pleasant part and the unpleasant part.

422
00:45:16,759 --> 00:45:19,963
And that we have to accept with this radical acceptance.

423
00:45:20,324 --> 00:45:27,878
But what I do with it afterwards, the misery and horror that I create afterwards, is totally my own doing.

424
00:45:29,021 --> 00:45:31,505
Nobody can make me angry, nobody can make me sad.

425
00:45:31,844 --> 00:45:44,840
If that was so, if it was so that people could make me angry, could make me sad, could make me depressed, could make me happy, then to become fully liberated, I'd have to get rid of you all.

426
00:45:46,822 --> 00:45:49,465
Because full liberation is perfect happiness.

427
00:45:50,425 --> 00:45:58,675
It is because we create our own happiness, our sadness, that we can become, each of us, individually liberated before other people.

428
00:46:01,878 --> 00:46:10,931
So that is also part of understanding of this not self, not substance.

429
00:46:11,152 --> 00:46:12,695
Nothing is substantial.

430
00:46:13,615 --> 00:46:15,639
So that's what our practice is doing.

431
00:46:15,980 --> 00:46:26,335
It's guiding us to see impermanence in a much more direct way, in a much more experiential way, that things actually do come to an end.

432
00:46:27,237 --> 00:46:30,601
And these exercises that we've mentioned around death

433
00:46:30,885 --> 00:46:33,891
And around, especially that other one about saying goodbye.

434
00:46:34,192 --> 00:46:35,795
See, constantly saying goodbye.

435
00:46:36,396 --> 00:46:37,418
Thank you, goodbye.

436
00:46:37,599 --> 00:46:38,400
Thank you, goodbye.

437
00:46:38,760 --> 00:46:43,429
You have a pleasant meal with somebody and then when it's finished you say thank you, goodbye.

438
00:46:43,490 --> 00:46:44,291
You don't say that to them.

439
00:46:44,331 --> 00:46:46,295
You're saying it internally.

440
00:46:48,284 --> 00:46:49,766
Say that internally to yourself.

441
00:46:51,228 --> 00:47:00,121
And every time you see a good DVD or any time you've had some degree of happiness, actually be grateful for it.

442
00:47:00,440 --> 00:47:05,688
Really accept that there was a time when I was happy and then goodbye.

443
00:47:06,108 --> 00:47:12,097
And that allows us to keep finishing, to keep bringing to an end because we don't like to see endings.

444
00:47:12,077 --> 00:47:18,485
And that's something you could do tomorrow, is to put more accent on seeing the ending of things.

445
00:47:18,846 --> 00:47:25,775
The seeing of beginning of things we're habituated to, because beginning for us means new, and new usually means good.

446
00:47:27,016 --> 00:47:28,918
But end usually means bad.

447
00:47:28,958 --> 00:47:34,905
And although we see the rising star, the great pop star, nobody ever knows what happens to them.

448
00:47:34,925 --> 00:47:36,027
They just disappear.

449
00:47:36,068 --> 00:47:39,672
So...

450
00:47:40,157 --> 00:47:45,443
This seeing of anicca, the dukkha is much more psychological, it's much more felt.

451
00:47:45,802 --> 00:47:54,010
You can grasp it much more quickly because you can see, you can feel the unsatisfactoriness and the way that we're attaching to things.

452
00:47:55,172 --> 00:48:06,882
And the anatta is slightly more difficult to see, but it's there to be seen by constantly pointing to our experiences.

453
00:48:07,021 --> 00:48:08,163
There is, there.

454
00:48:09,605 --> 00:48:09,945
And

455
00:48:10,313 --> 00:48:12,034
and that business of no control.

456
00:48:12,076 --> 00:48:16,983
The whole idea of a self is that it's in control.

457
00:48:17,023 --> 00:48:23,552
If it's not in control of something, the control center must be in somewhere else.

458
00:48:26,056 --> 00:48:31,804
If I am my body, I should be able to say, right, from now on you're never going to get ill and you're not going to grow old.

459
00:48:32,625 --> 00:48:33,806
Full stop.

460
00:48:33,972 --> 00:48:41,483
But it's the fact that the control center of the body is within the body and not in that which wants the body to not grow old, etc.

461
00:48:42,324 --> 00:48:43,726
Shows me that it can't be me.

462
00:48:48,355 --> 00:48:54,925
And then finally, just cutting down to the quick about that relationship.

463
00:48:56,807 --> 00:48:58,090
Constantly questioning it.

464
00:49:00,179 --> 00:49:11,050
And remember that although the talk has been mainly about undermining what is delusive, remember that as we do that, the opposite arises quite naturally.

465
00:49:12,351 --> 00:49:15,375
As soon as we cut through a delusion, wisdom arises naturally.

466
00:49:16,295 --> 00:49:24,684
Whereas delusion manifests in self-centeredness, selfishness, in aversion and in cruelty.

467
00:49:25,255 --> 00:49:27,818
The opposites just happen naturally.

468
00:49:27,838 --> 00:49:29,021
They just arise naturally.

469
00:49:29,581 --> 00:49:31,704
Generosity, love, and compassion.

470
00:49:32,867 --> 00:49:40,760
It's not as though you can't help them on a bit through exercise and practice, but it's not as though there's an intermediate state where there's nothing.

471
00:49:41,481 --> 00:49:43,844
Either you're cruel or you're compassionate.

472
00:49:43,864 --> 00:49:45,427
Either you're hateful or you're loving.

473
00:49:46,108 --> 00:49:49,474
There's no sort of intermediate state between those two.

474
00:49:51,394 --> 00:50:02,451
So the gift of practicing like this is a movement of our characters and personalities towards the beautiful.

475
00:50:02,710 --> 00:50:04,432
It just happens sort of naturally.

476
00:50:11,302 --> 00:50:11,884
So there's hope.

477
00:50:14,092 --> 00:50:21,344
I can only hope my words of being of some assistance have not created further confusion and despair.

478
00:50:22,005 --> 00:50:34,547
And that through your devotion to practice and careful investigation of these three characteristics of existence, you will become liberated sooner rather than later.

